<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-620-658  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 620 658.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 5 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Macs to speak 50 languages. (Macintosh)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zucker, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh IIcx (Microcomputer) (purchasing)Apple LaserWriter II NT (Computer printer) (purchasing).andO;Topic:     Australia. Department of Immigration and Ethnic AffairsComputer industryMicrocomputersLaser PrintersLanguage Translation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MACS TO SPEAK 50 LANGUAGES CANBERRA, AUSTRALIA, 1989 AUG 31 (NB) -- Some 29Apple Mac systems will be installed by the Australian department ofImmigration and Ethnic Affairs, to be used in word processing more than fiftydifferent languages.andP;  The department has 30 full-time translators, and alarge bank of contract translators.andP;  The machines (which beat IBM and Xeroxat tender) are Mac IIcx 2/40 with two-page monochrome monitors, scanner,modem and LaserWriter II printers.andP;  Some machines will be connected by anAppleShare network and others, more widely spread, will use the modems.andP;  Thesoftware is capable of handling complicated character sets such as those usedin Asia and the Middle East.andP;  (Paul Zucker/19890901)</TEXT></DOC>